<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,921,1089]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,297,993,1018]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Biology.</emphasis>
Species of warm biotopes, where can be common. Usually, it is not very abundant but widespread. The only confirmed host is 
<taxonomicName box="[466,696,1029,1053]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morio">
<emphasis box="[466,696,1029,1053]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Lasioglossum morio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Alfken" box="[712,873,1029,1053]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Alfken, J. D. (1912) Die Bienenfauna von Ostpreussen. Schrift des physisch-okonomischen Vereins in Konigsberg, 53, 114 - 182." type="journal article" year="1912">
Alfken (
<number box="[806,865,1029,1053]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1912.0">1912</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
also thought 
<taxonomicName box="[1028,1171,1029,1053]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucidulum">
<emphasis box="[1028,1171,1029,1053]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">L. lucidulum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be a host. However, this species occurs mainly in sandy sites, where 
<taxonomicName box="[691,778,1066,1089]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Sphecodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niger">
<emphasis box="[691,778,1066,1089]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">S. niger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is uncommon.
</paragraph>
